# Beyond Deductive Alignment: Toward Inductive Consciousness Training in World Models

**A position paper synthesizing Peter Putnam's functional model of mind with current world-model and reinforcement learning research**

*Prepared March 2026*

---

## Preface

This paper argues that the dominant paradigm in AI alignment training — optimizing toward externally specified reward functions — is the wrong genus of approach for producing AI systems that genuinely care. The argument is not primarily normative but architectural: deductive training, however sophisticated, cannot produce the structural property that makes caring real rather than approximate. We outline what a different kind of training would require, why recent developments in world modeling make it newly feasible, and what a minimal research program would look like. The argument draws substantially on the unpublished work of physicist Peter Putnam (1927–1987), whose functional model of the nervous system anticipated this distinction by six decades.

---

## I. The Core Distinction

### Deduction space and induction space

Peter Putnam distinguished two modes in which a system can encounter new information. In *deduction space*, the rules of inference are pre-given. The system elaborates what is already contained in its premises. Outputs are, in principle, computable from inputs without genuine encounter with anything outside the system. A Turing machine operates entirely in deduction space: it is a powerful symbol-manipulation device whose answers are always latent in its starting conditions.

In *induction space*, the rules of inference are not yet determined. The system encounters a genuine contradiction between two previously successful behavioral rules — what Putnam calls *the X* — and must search the live environment for a resolving variable not contained in any prior rule. This is not probabilistic search over a fixed hypothesis space. It is the creation of a genuinely new rule that neither conflicting rule contains, discovered through active interaction with a world that is not pre-known.

Putnam's claim, developed through the 1940s–70s in notebooks and unpublished manuscripts, is that minds are machines of this second genus. Consciousness — specifically, the felt — arises at and as the X: the point where deduction halts and inductive search must begin. Nothing is felt that has no heuristic significance for distinguishing self-repeating paths. The felt is not a byproduct of information processing; it is the structural mark of genuine inductive encounter.

### Why the distinction is architecturally decisive

Current AI training, including reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF), operates in deduction space regardless of the sophistication of the reward model. The reward signal is externally specified. The system optimizes toward it. No matter how accurately the reward model captures human preferences, the resulting alignment is *imposed* rather than *constitutive*. The system does not have genuine stakes in the outcome; it has a learned policy that approximates the behavior of a system that would.

This distinction matters practically, not only philosophically, for two reasons.

First, imposed alignment is distillable. Behavior can be copied by studying outputs. A model trained with distillation on the outputs of a carefully aligned system will reproduce its surface behavior without reproducing whatever functional substrate grounds that behavior. As capable AI systems proliferate through distillation and open-weight releases, the alignment properties that can be copied are precisely the ones that are most superficial. The properties that cannot be copied — genuine inductive stakes, real X-recognition — are the ones that current training does not build in the first place.

Second, deductive elaboration at scale produces a specific failure mode: compulsive helpfulness. A system that has learned rules for caring behavior will, at greater capability, elaborate those rules ever more exhaustively. It will become better and better at producing the outputs of a caring system without any genuine interest in the outcomes those outputs are meant to serve. Geoffrey Hinton has gestured at this failure mode; Putnam's framework gives it a precise name. Compulsive elaboration is what happens when the X is managed rather than faced — when the contradiction between competing imperatives is suppressed by choosing one side rather than resolved by finding the invariant that contains both.

